  "why": "The paper introduces LLM-FUZZER, a framework for generating jailbreak prompts. The entire focus of the methodology and evaluation is on the effectiveness and efficiency of this failure discovery process. The experiments are designed to quantify the performance of the fuzzer using metrics like Jailbreaking Question Number (JQN), Attack Success Rate (ASR), and resource consumption (QBC, TBC). These metrics measure the fuzzer's ability to find failures, but do not provide any diagnostic insight into why the generated prompts are successful. The paper conducts ablation studies, but these are aimed at diagnosing the components of the fuzzer itself (e.g., the contribution of different mutation operators or seed selection strategies), not the underlying vulnerabilities of the target LLMs. The research is strictly black-box and does not analyze model internals, nor does it present a statistical analysis of failure patterns that would suggest root causes like dataset bias or reliance on spurious features.",
